76561198006872048,Recommended,439720,21550673,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,Taurus84,"Review as of patch 1.2.0.5 at 29.02.2016:Hey, I am not a native english-speaker so please go easy on any typos you may find :-)I bought the game at the initial steam release and had a lot of crashes. Then I set the game to run in Direct X 9 Legacy mode which helped a lot for me and I get barely any crashes at all.The good about the game is... if you can run it, its pretty fun. The price tag of 11,99 Euro atm is in my opinion set too high, since the game has still some serious crashes (can still not go to game settings from ingame and have to use the game settings out of game before starting the game to change things). Also the economy and number of ships is not nearly as complex as for example a X-series game (which the game creator is a modder of). I think the game still lacks a lot of content and it could need a more fleshed out economy. Also the battles are a lot too fast... sure there is a combat mod that makes some changes, so that combat is slower and more meaningful than just pewpew boom battleship gone, but I think the core game should also lean a lot more in such a direction, basically more away from that arcady feeling and more to a full-scale 4x where you have a slow build-up and your bases and economy has a bigger meaning. It would be also nice to do more with your own sectors when you have some... as far as it is atm you build stations into your sectors and thats pretty much it... I would like to have more defence structures, maybe even minefields and such... I would like to be able to customise the automated patrolships in my sector (amount and kind of and such) maybe that could be also imbued by adding for example a fleet headquarter for stronger patrols and fighter bases for more smaller patrols or something like that.All in all the game has a good idea behind it. The technical execution is not that good atm, it needs quite more polishing.  Also it needs a lot more base game content, sure the game is heavily modable and modders already did come up with smaller mods but to get more people into the game (and more bigger mods in the end) it would be good to lure in a bigger audience with more and of course more fleshed out content. What would also help to make the economy more meaningful... make ship building for the own faction and the AI more complex and as I said combat slower and more meaningful. Give players and AI more tools to protect their assets and add more content in general (would like a lot more ship types like corvettes, cruisers with different niches and something bigger than a battleship maybe to have as a flagship). Thats in my opinion what would help this game a lot and take it from ""oh a small nice game that I play for a few hours"" to ""WOW... and its also heavily modable... I am so gonna make a mod for it and play that game forever"".I know as a user its always kind of easy to point out the weaker parts of a game and say ""oh that needs more work"" and all. Still keep in mind this is a one man show and he is fixing as fast as possible and will add more content to it as far as I did read on the forums (and I believe him). The game will get there to be that masterpiece we all would like to have, but it still needs time and some deep balancing changes.So... why a positive review?If you want to help a dev in getting the game to a broader audience and dont mind the 11,99 Euro price tag you should jump in with both feet. If you have a lot of crashes and graphical odd behavior like me, try the Direct X9 legacy mode, helped me. Also I think you have to see this kind of game here as some kind of early access and not as finished triple A title.So If you have no problem to get a game thats not labeled Early Access but should be, then buy... help the dev make it bigger and better with your money, feedback and maybe even mods (as far as I did read he also needs more ship models and stations and such, if you have some or know how to make some, maybe contact him?)If you mind buying a game for 12,99 Euro that needs quite some work (not meaning the content and content balance here, but especially the technical side), then wait a while and see how it turns out.I think the game is worth playing. If you want to have a more polished experience its worth having it on your radar for a while and then jump in."
76561198011187900,Recommended,439720,21448262,"Posted: 25 February, 2016",all,Daeromont,"Although the learning curve on this game is somewhat high due to a lack of current or complete documentation (still in devlopement), I find Unending Galaxy (UG) to be a refreshing 4X game with a challenging AI, broad spectrum of potential scenarios and replayability, and just plain fun to play.  Once a player understands the controls, it is comparitively quick to play compared to other 4X games and yet still has a great deal of depth and a range of options for playability for various styles.    For a person like me who has a lot of personal demands upon my time, this has been a great way to feed my 4X game appetite.    I feel like in my dozens of hours of game play that I have hardly hit the surface of the game on many levels, and yet, the economic system and combat are straightforward and fast.  At times, I micromanage as much as possible while at others, I put my ships on autopilot and sit back and watch the action.    It has the feel of a universe which I am still exploring...and a game which will occupy many hours and days of my time."
